<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-10T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-10T04:00:00-05:00" n="411" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d411">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 659.119/367</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-10T10:00:00+01:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 10, 1918, 10 a.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 10.02 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>219. War Trade Board from Doctor <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_TAE1">Taylor</persName>:</p>
                            <p>No. 976. If Danes accept your shipping proposal there remains still
                                the matter of exports to Germany. At last meeting with me in <pb facs="0499" n="1333" xml:id="pg_1333"/> Washington Danes
                                advanced new proposals for exports to Germany that could not be
                                regarded as related to previous negotiations. Acceptance by them of
                                our shipping proposal does not carry with it acceptance by us of
                                their new proposal of export of fish and agricultural products. This
                                new proposal they stated had been imposed on them in order to secure
                                immunity from new enemy prize court rule. These proposals French and
                                British regard as impossible just as we did. I will take up with
                                Allies acceptation of export clause along line of old agreement and
                                report.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Laughlin</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>